<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12017c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12017c">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12017c"> 17(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ druidesses / ashen arrows shot coppertipped / against &eacute;clairs</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Un coll&egrave;ge de neuf proph&eacute;tesses appel&eacute;es S&egrave;nes habitait ce sanctuaire d&eacute;fendu par la f&ocirc;ret sacr&eacute;e et le sauvage oc&eacute;an. Sur ces rochers et aux alentours, les druidesses c&eacute;l&eacute;braient leurs rites, leurs myst&egrave;res, leurs sacrifices. Les marins qui affrontaient la mer venaient les consulter dans cette caverne. C&apos;est l&agrave; qu&apos;elles rendaient leurs oracles, qu&apos;elles vendaient &agrave; prix d&apos;or ces fl&egrave;ches magiques en bois de fr&ecirc;ne, &agrave; pointe de cuivre, barbel&eacute;es de plumes de faucon, qui &eacute;taient cens&eacute;es d&eacute;tourner les orages, et que les Gaulois lan&ccedil;aient dans la nue quand grondait la foudre. <br><font color="green">[A college of nine prophetesses called Senes lived in this sanctuary defended by the sacred forest and the savage ocean. On these rocks and environs, the druidesses celebrated their rites, their mysteries, their sacrifices. The sailors who ventured out onto the sea came and consulted them in their cavern. It is there that they gave their oracles, that they sold for gold their magic arrows in ash wood and with a copper point, decorated with falcon plumes, which were rumored to turn away thunder storms, and which the Gauls shot at the sky when thunder roared in the skies.]</font> <small> &Eacute;douard Schur&eacute;, <a name="ESLL" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ESLL"><cite title="source">Les Grandes L&eacute;gendes de France</cite></a> (1892) 143</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
